A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama’s Re-Election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight electoral fraud.
The Brennan Center considers it a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is rarer in the United States than the number of people killed by lightning.
In fact, Republican lawyers have only identified 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the United States is responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It is in this spirit that a majority of US governments enacted new laws from 2009 making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which saw the addition of 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 draft laws restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in 2011 alone.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo ID card and proof of U.S. citizenship.
Moreover, these laws also reduce the voting periods in advance, invalidate the right to register as a voter on the day of the election and remove citizens with a judicial record their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no U.S. state required voters to present a photo ID card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana's law in 2008.
The republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo ID card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of U.S. citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo ID cards issued by a government agency in their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than a hundred dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities, and low-income people.
In fact, 25 percent of African Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000; 18 percent of citizens over the age of 65; and 20 percent of voters aged 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, who are considered to vote more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their ID card with a photo issued by their institution.
On the other hand, these same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote cards issued by these clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to make such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
But it turns out that two out of three Hispanic voters favor the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers sponsored in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the registration rate of new voters by 17% in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of the voters who voted in advance were African-Americans, while the latter represented only 13% of the state's voters.
The same goes for Hispanics.
These represented only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In contrast, whites who made up 76% of voters represented only 46% of voters who voted in advance.
Of course, Democratic legislators and their supporters have vigorously opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The Attorney General of the United States intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have passed laws requiring the presentation of an identity card with a photo.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed and see it as an obvious goal to influence the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that the states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively affect the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Prostate cancer screening: pass the test or not?
Indeed, the PSA test would sometimes present erroneous results, with false negative results or false positives, which lead to unnecessary medical interventions.
What makes men even more reluctant to pass screening tests?
Pass the test or not?
We asked for the opinion of two specialists.
In studies conducted in the United States, there was a lot of contamination between control groups, so it is difficult to interpret these data and have firm recommendations.
Another study, the European study, concluded that there was a difference in mortality between patients who had a screening and those who did not.
This study also showed, with follow-up after 12 years, that we have between 30 and 40% more chances of having metastases if we are not screened.
So I recommend the test from age 50, or from age 40 if you have a direct relative who has already had prostate cancer.
Men of African-American descent are also more at risk.
The key is to make the right decision once a cancer has been detected.
There are aggressive cancers and others that are indolent.
We really need to make the patient understand the degree of risk of his cancer, by offering him the possible options, by not necessarily treating prostate cancers that do not affect long-term life, and by opting instead, in these cases, for active surveillance of the disease.
Today, many men who are diagnosed with cancer will not be treated because their cancer is not aggressive and does not threaten their lives.
They will be suggested to do active monitoring and if the disease progresses, they will be offered treatment.
The criteria for deciding who should or should not be treated are increasingly being determined with precision.
I still recommend taking the test.
But the important thing is to have a discussion with your doctor to determine if we should go through it or not.
In collaboration with the International Urology Society, Movember has created a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of the PSA test.
This document (in English for the moment, a translation will be available soon) can be downloaded at: http://ca.movember.com/mens-health/prostate-cancer-screening
Preventing the disease
Unfortunately, there is no miracle recipe for preventing cancer.
Despite advances in research, adopting good lifestyle habits remains the best way to reduce the risk of suffering from them.
It is estimated that if everyone ate well and moved enough, 30% of cancers could be prevented.
“If no one smoked anymore, this rate would rise to at least 50%,” said André Beaulieu, a spokesman for the Canadian Cancer Society.
On the other hand, it is estimated that about 10% of cancers are caused by heredity.
Many of them are also completely unexplained.
For the Canadian Cancer Society, the fight against smoking remains a priority, despite the decrease in the number of smokers.
Cigarette smoking is linked to 85% of lung cancer cases.
It is also a risk factor for many others.
This greatly harms people’s health.
"Even today, there are 1.5 million smokers in Quebec," said spokesman André Beaulieu.
10 years after quitting smoking, the risk of dying from cancer drops by half.
The Weight
Obesity and overweight also contribute to the onset of the disease, according to the CSC.
They would increase the risk of breast, colon and rectum cancer, esophagus, pancreas and uterus cancer.
“Research shows that regular practice of physical activity throughout a lifetime protects against colon cancer,” it added.
The food
The organization also recommends limiting its consumption of red meat.
Too much of it increases the risk of colorectal cancer.
Butchers also, and they should be avoided.
The preservation of meat by smoking, drying or salting can lead to the formation of carcinogens.
"The latter can damage the body's cells and lead to the development of cancer," it said.
The vitamins
In recent years, several scientists have studied the links between vitamin supplements and cancer.
However, their research is not conclusive at this time.
Studies on vitamin E are contradictory, according to the CSC.
While one of them found a decrease in the risk of prostate cancer, another noted an increase.
The effect of vitamin D on cancer is also not clearly established.
In addition, Mr. Beaulieu stresses the importance of talking about his concerns and his family history with his doctor.
"Getting a screening test doesn't give you cancer."
The Higgs boson
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson created quite a stir last summer, and for good reason.
It is believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then, this is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model - our best, or "less worst" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been empirically observed.
But for physicists, it's not entirely certain that it's the Higgs yet.
It is known without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, but data is still missing to be perfectly sure.
Let's assume it's Higgs anyway, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this lower world, a fatally unavoidable law that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule - and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Now even though particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: Pauli's exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" consisting roughly of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify the particles into two categories.
In one corner there are good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey Pauli’s principle.
And in the other are stirring bosons, a dirty band of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are then divided into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not discuss here, and the "particle of force", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
These bosons, it should be noted here, are not all as exotic beasts as one might think.
In fact, if you manage to read this chronicle, it is thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon, or the "particle of light" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disrupts” the electromagnetic field at this precise location, much like a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" arises an electromagnetic wave (of light, or of infrared, or of ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore, one of the bosons "carriers of force".
More stable field
The same goes for the Higgs boson, with this difference being that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, one must reach very, very high energies, a bit as if it were a frozen pond of which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN's - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27-kilometer ring! - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
Indeed, not all particles, nor all materials, interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never hold itself on a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while others (such as the photon, yours) do not.
Now, what "can bring" all this research, asks Mrs. Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SMS), and it also allows physicists to examine any gap between observations and predictions of the SMS.
There are many who would like to find it, because the slightest difference could open a door on a "new physics" and plug some holes in the Model.
This one, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-oops!).
But no such discrepancies have been found at CERN so far.
Repercussions
The repercussions of these researches in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. All-the-World, they are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will not be.
Note: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers at Bell Laboratories did not suspect the revolution that their work was going to trigger.
They envisioned scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, physicist Willard Boyle – who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 – has already told us that at first the laser was rather seen as a “lab gadget”.
I imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969, during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not his original intention at all, now serves as an "eye" to all digital cameras in the world, and won him the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it does mean that, really, we never know...
Palliative care - The best way to die... <0x7C> The Duty
With its Commission dying in dignity, Quebec has recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly as a bill is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this essential area.
Duty tried to take a closer look.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that gnawed him had left him a two-year hiatus.
"They had given me five years to live, I was seven years old," he said, half-fig half-grain, lying in his bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s still a shock, you can’t be prepared for that,” he says.
The disease does its job: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the toilet alone, and even eating alone.
Attached to an appetizing lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped to eat, resigned.
Courageous, he even manages to smile, talks to strangers who do business around him, bring him his medicines, offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is that I’m cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this ailment.
"In our life, we learn that a man pisses standing," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois house.
Regressing to the child stage, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“It depends on the person’s ability to accept regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great moments take place in the very heart of this regression.
Patients who enter the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this point, the "team of doctors and nurses" that surrounds them no longer provides so-called "curative" care.
For Ms. A., 89, the worst fear is to die “consciously and suffocated”.
But the illness made me discover my children.
“I have good children,” she adds.
“I don’t have wishes in life anymore,” she says, before agreeing to wear a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting, in the next few days, for one last visit from her son from Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois, we provide, with a group of volunteers, body care and food assistance.
It is palliative care that is given when there is nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is a palliative care bed for 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little when we know that we all end up dying one day.
Here, life goes on in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors in the house.
Whether it’s physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
At the time of death, we will accept to provide oral care to the brandy or Pepsi, as requested.
Diabetics will no longer be required to control their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night, we served a beer to Mr. X, who died the night before.
This morning, his son will finish the beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help loved ones as much as patients,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois house, the days follow but do not resemble each other.
Alongside an old 93-year-old man who enjoys his last family gathering in the courtyard, well tucked into his pillows while drinking in his honor, a 36-year-old dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two young children, after trying everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds that are occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois home come from their homes, 47% come from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient has reached the terminal phase of their life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois House and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is precisely this great deficiency in Quebec's health care that scares several physicians specialized in palliative care the adoption of a law governing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto, signed by palliative care summits including Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to testify to their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not performing well enough to ensure that everyone will be entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
Recently, she says, I have seen a patient spend 14 days in emergency, in great pain, without doing what is necessary to relieve her.
I'm afraid patients only ask to die because they don't get the proper care.
And at the same time, several oncologists cling to their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard's hopes of survival were already low when she gave up trying chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I stopped fighting, she told me.
Yet, she told me that I was finished!
No almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask to die thank caregivers for not accessing their request after they have been relieved of their pain by a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful in the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients would be refractory to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, which involves sleeping the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can no longer pretend not to hear that part of the suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved patient will have the opportunity to have this palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved always say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want you to euthanize me,” it means “I want to be relieved.”
