A Constitution with forceps in Egypt
This is a new poker move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt remains more divided than ever around the constitutional declaration, which temporarily grants it full powers, it has decided to play its part.
Taking everyone short, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given this Assembly two more months to finish its work.
Egypt has been relying on a provisional text for almost two years, amended several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal fraud.
This new initiative has only increased the gap in the country.
For his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delirium", continuing to "treach his word" and "walk the law".
On the side of its supporters, it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible, by speeding up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 15 days.
A very short period of time which obliges the Brothers to abandon their project to explain the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the President, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy, as the protests rage throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor, as he said in an interview with American weekly Time.
Especially since this use of a hasty vote is due to the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I keep the full powers", these must supposedly end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent assembly, largely Islamist, voted on the text yesterday.
Most of the Liberals missed the call.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, believing that they could not assert their views.
The representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society had done the same.
In order for the necessary quorum to be reached, 11 substitute members were added in haste yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Unsurprisingly, it is most often unanimously that the articles were voted on.
Some commentators were amused by the fact that one of the only differences of the day was expressed around... the hour of prayer, with some members of the committee believing that the constituent's pendulum was wrongly set.
The text, which was still being voted on last night, contains 234 articles.
Objects of all attention, Article 2 remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, stipulating that "the principles of sharia are the principal source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is a major demand, hoped to be able to replace "principles" with "rules", which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy," replied the Liberals, who saw it only as a communication blow.
Because according to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They include Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to verifying the conformity of laws with sharia law.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "people called to speak out are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
We can see the beginnings of a theocracy.”
The fears of the Liberals are further agitated by the fact that the next rector of this university should be much less moderate than the current one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution, we remain within the framework of the civil state.
Most of the jurists who have worked on this text are not ulemas but academics, for some trained in the French system" tempers Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges "that there may be ambiguity around Article 220, because the terms used borrow from religious vocabulary.
It refers to the "fiqh" in particular [Islamic jurisprudence, ndlr].
And the question may arise in the future as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to rule on it.”
Beyond its religious aspect, the text voted yesterday is highly criticized because of the extensive powers it grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood argues that these are significantly reduced in comparison to what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers conferred on the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the consideration of the Defence budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a National Defence Council.
Nor will the trials of civilians in military courts, as requested by human rights associations, be prohibited.
The latter also express their concerns about the text, which they consider to be liberticide.
The offence of blasphemy is maintained and insult is now banned, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially in the press.
In addition, there is no longer any article that speaks to the protection of women, says Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was supposed to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled this afternoon.
The head of state's supporters will march on Saturday.
In Israel, holy places, the center of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land brings together the grandeur of biblical truths, modern comfort and wild nature.
Argumenty i Fakty has selected five major reasons to visit Israel.
Go Worship the Holy Places
Unmissable: the banks of the Jordan, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that whoever enters these "baptismal grounds" will be touched by divine Grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where the water was turned into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he calmed the storm or where fishing was miraculous.
It is at this precise place that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is well in Jerusalem.
Believers walk along the Rue de la Sufferance or the Way of the Cross (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the praetorium), where the trial was held, then leads through the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to the one of the Stone of the Annunciation and the tomb.
This is where the Christian center of the world is located, a symbol of humanity’s salvation.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified grew.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Wall of Lamentations which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC.
According to tradition, people of different confessions leave small words with prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the fortress of Massada, a former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC for his family.
These ruins are located on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there by their own means.
For others, a cable car takes them to this summit full of history.
To the north of the country, between 1 600 and 2 040 m of altitude, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont which welcomes many tourists in winter.
A shuttle can take you from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are a total of 45 km long.
The old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all in one stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth the detour.
First of all: the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the ancient Qumran manuscripts, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly exhibits the paintings of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths composed of moldings of visitors and supervisors of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire Rodin's sculptures.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the Children's Memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter and enter into total darkness.
Stars are scintillating.
Then you hear the names of the Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned in it.
Health and well-being
Israel’s three major seaside resorts are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each one offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can swim in the Red Sea even in winter, as the water temperature does not fall below 21° while that of the air can reach 23°.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim in it all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure water contains brine and very easily retains the bathers, even those who do not know how to swim.
The landscapes that surround it are of a surreal beauty.
We come here to carry out a treatment based on salt water, lemon, curative mud and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to simply relax.
Discover the secrets of Antiquity
They are guarded by the old city of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in the Greek and Egyptian legends of antiquity.
According to legend, it is here that Noah built his ark and that Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived here himself a long and happy life.
Tourists especially like to walk in the narrow alleys that bear the name of the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you touch the walls of the street corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can meet newlyweds who have come to do photo shoots from all over Israel and even from other countries.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk in the Roman theater, "conquer" the fortress of the crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, notably Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theatre is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to Tourists
If you’re going to Israel, don’t worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, as they are easily exchangeable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
As for urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
Travel in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1h30.
In Israel, Jewish tradition wants to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport cease their activity.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants, and hotels only serve kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, scaleless fish, and dishes made up of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of dishes based on lamb and beef, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish pasta, different sauces, balls of chickpeas, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many well-fed cats that walk in the high air.
We can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars in the evening.
These cats love passing places and do not refuse to be eaten.
Car rental varies depending on the brand from $37 for 24h (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Insurance costs $15 per day.
Renting a bike will cost you 15 shekels a day.
On average, a visit to the museum costs 30 shekels.
The Language of Numbers
Three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel in 2012.
These were mainly people who came to travel and rest from the United States, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine.
118.8 miles of Ukrainian tourists went to the Promised Land from January to October 2012, 51% more than in 2010, before visa cancellation on February 9, 2011.
"Who has a language, goes to Moscow": migrants save money to learn the language
As MPs and human rights activists debate what the mandatory language test law will do, fraudsters selling “false” certificates have already made their appearance in the country.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of the time, they are nationals of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal: to earn money to help their families stay at home.
Since December 1, a law has come into force and stipulates that every migrant worker will have to pass a Russian examination.
For the time being, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the services, housing, services to individuals and retail.
However, over time, the Federal Migration Service promises, testing will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will be necessary to validate the knowledge of the language, but also that of the History of Russia and the foundations of law.
You will need to validate your language skills in Russian to obtain and renew your work permit.
Only nationals of countries where Russian has official language status are exempt.
Persons who obtained certificates or degrees of education before the fall of the USSR in 1991 are also not affected by this law.
Benefit, negative attitude and protection of rights
The network of examination centers will be under the aegis of the Russian-language Pushkin Institute, the University of Peoples' Friendship, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the exams in all cities of the country: more than 160 centers have already been opened throughout the country.
This initiative to introduce reviews was supported by members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Service.
But, before the law came into force, human rights defenders have already repeatedly asked the question in the press: what will it give?
What will the obligation to know Russian change for Russians and immigrants?
First of all, according to the representatives of the migration service, this will reduce the number of people suffering from "slavery at work".
Many talk about defending the rights of migrant workers, says the director of the office of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan, Victor Sebelev.
The protection of rights must begin before they leave.
Only an organized selection system will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, without training, those who do not know the language and who do not have medical certificates.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future migrant is destined to meet dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a "journey" in an overcrowded house where he and dozens of his fellows will be tormented for months without food and paper and will have to trim between 12 and 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrants.
“At their house, they are promised one thing, and when they arrive, they are cheated, they are taken away from their passport, and they do not get the expected salary,” says Tolib Charipov, head of the Directorate of Migration Services for the work of the Tajikistan Migration Service.
Don't argue with me, Officer!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to come and make money in Russia trust that they not only do not know the language of the country where they wish to go, but also that they write with difficulty in their own language.
It is not their fault, of course, but their misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to follow even a suitable primary education.
Indeed, their families do not even have anything to feed their children without talking about dressing them properly and equipping them for school.
As soon as they reach adolescence, these young people start making money as soon as the opportunity presents itself.
It's hard when you don't know the language, they say.
"You feel diminished and diminished."
Human rights defenders, however, note an important aspect of the language law.
The examinations will be intended only for migrants who have legal status.
Without status, there will be no formal examination or work afterwards.
Yet most migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or defense to enter"
Many immigrants explain that it is not so easy to get an official status in Russia.
The reason? Administrative barriers and always these language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: between 12 and 16 thousand rubles.
And then, you can get a fake registration quickly for only 1,500 rubles.
The Russian police know that we have false documents, that we do not have a record, hence the cases of extortion.
"They are asking us 100, 200 rubles, what to buy cigarettes, tea," Oumed Khouchkadamov, a Tajikistani, told reporters.
“Hurry up, don’t skimp and buy yourself a beautiful work of art.”
From the first day of the language law's entry into force, it was discovered that migrant registration papers were not the only ones to be false.
Several false language examination certificates have already been confiscated by employees of the Federal Migration Service.
The falsified papers come out of an ordinary color printer.
Of course, their new owners did not take them for granted: every migrant who hoped to facilitate the task of examinations had to pay seven thousand rubles for this document.
It is two and a half times more expensive than the official procedure: it will cost the migrant worker three thousand rubles.
Power representatives and human rights defenders agree that the short-term goal is to protect the system from corruption so that it is impossible to simply buy these “paper bits”.
The authorities may give migrant workers who have not been able to validate the first-time examination time to take language courses.
In addition, immigrants who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve actively communicating with people.
The Ministry of the Interior does not deal with the arms market
The share of crimes involving legal weapons is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior proposes to tighten the law against the bearers of civilian weapons.
This is the reaction of the authorities in the face of recent incidents: whether it is the shootings carried out during marriages or the murder organized by the Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov, which killed seven.
The police want to ban the wearing of rubber bullets in public places and raise the legal age of obtaining a gun license by increasing it from 18 to 21 years.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, who promised that amendments to the arms law would be introduced to the State Duma soon.
Not everyone is satisfied with the fact that the Russian authorities are trying to solve the problem by "tightening the screw".
An open letter appeared on the Internet in which its authors, representatives of various shooting centers, demand to abandon "this senseless hardening".
The percentage of crimes committed with a registered weapon is minimal, Vasily Lesnikov, a lawyer and crime specialist for the BBC, told the Russian service.
According to statistics from the Ministry of the Interior, over a period of six months in 2012, 142 crimes were committed with a firearm registered in the police services, while 1,168 thousand crimes were registered during the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the strengthening of civil arms laws will not prevent criminals from sourcing to the black market.
According to them, today in Moscow you can find any weapon for a reasonable price.
However, the Ministry of the Interior claims that it controls the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factory to the officer
The black market for weapons is provided through several channels.
The main channels are five, says Victor Baranets, a retired colonel who served for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the Headquarters.
Screenshot taken from a site taking orders for weapons
The first is the "military trace", that is, the weapons that were stolen during the military operations in the Caucasus.
"These weapons were stolen by Russian officers, but also by Caucasians," Baranets said.
The second type of weapons from the black market are those stolen by criminals to law enforcement.
Baranets explains that these are both weapons stolen from police stocks and those stolen directly from law enforcement officials.
Illegal pistols go on sale from military warehouses.
Many of them have often suffered explosions.
"Certified versions indicate that some fires were deliberately started to conceal the deficit," the former military official said.
For Baranets, the weapons manufacturers are there for something.
“We see private weapons factories that do not compete with the competition in the international market and flow weapons into the black market, especially in Moscow,” said one expert.
One of the other sources of the black market is smuggling.
A significant proportion of guns and machine guns come from poor countries, such as Kyrgyzstan.
“There is a local production, sometimes artisanal, a mafia formed and organizes the supply,” adds the former military.
Where do the weapons come from?
The experts assessed the approximate share of each source of illegal weapons on the black market.
A report on the issue was prepared in 2011 by the Centre for Problem Analysis and Public Administration Studies.
Specialists analyzed the reports of the Ministry of the Interior and Rosstat, criminal files and public data of the portals related to weapons.
The vast majority of illegal weapons, the researchers explain, come from the army and law enforcement agencies.
Half of the weapons on the black market were found there "by the fault of employees whose work is related to weapons," the report said.
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from places of military conflict, 14% are stolen at the time of manufacture and 5% are from "clandestine sheets".
An armory salesman and consultant who asked to remain anonymous says that for a long time no one has bought the weapons found by these specialists of the clandestine search; they are too old.
Most often, according to him, sellers will look for the new goods in the military warehouses.
The person buys a unit through a sign, for example a TT gun.
We deliver it to him by passing the merchandise through a grill.
"He transports it to the city and sells it for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>900 per unit with two loaders," he says.
“It is true that the police are aware of all cases, so when crimes are about to be solved, they make a check purchase from illegal arms dealers,” the seller adds.
"Like in a luxury shop "
The seller and the buyer are usually found through knowledge.
I consulted sites, blogs, until a guy shows up and proposes to come to the Begovaya train station where someone had to take me to a "corner" to shop.
The price of the gun, they gave it to me on the spot
Victor Baranets as Military Observer
To find a gun, I need to know someone who has a contact, explains the seller. I know someone, but I do not trust him.
There are sellers in the markets, but there you have to come also saying, for example, "From such a person, who asked me to transmit that his daughter has lost a tooth."
Now I even buy a pair of American fists with the help of a person I trust.
He only gives them to me because he knows I won't give them to him.
The little ones are looking for weapons in different ways.
Former military Victor Baranets tried as a buyer of illegal weapons in the mid-1990s when he was preparing to publish an article on the subject.
The patterns, according to him, have not changed.
He was given a photo album in which there was "everything we want".
“I believed in a luxury boutique,” recalls the soldier.
