We began to focus on the issues of reproduction in space with a focus on flora.
Half a century ago, experiments were being carried out on plants.
Four generations of small peas grown in orbit did not differ in any way from terrestrial varieties.
Then, insects, small reproductive drosophilic flies, were put into orbit.
In 1979, quail eggs were sent into space to see how a weightless embryo was developing.
A completely normal chick is obtained at the exit.
Then the problems begin.
"The problem is that the chick has to find a support, it has to get on its feet and start moving," says the director of the laboratory of the Institute of Medical and Biological Problems of the Russian Academy of Sciences (IMBP) Vladimir Sychev.
When no support was found, the chicks moved in a disorderly manner.
And after 10 hours, the newborns saw their instincts completely atrophied.
The chicks did not react to light or sound.
Unfortunately, they would simply die after four days.
"We have rubbed their eyes twice, then we gave up, because it is simply impossible to work with them there," says Vladimir Sychev, noting the failure of the experiment with chicks in space.
The last biological "miniature ark" with animals was sent into orbit 16 years ago.
The experiments will continue in the spring of 2013.
However, the biosatellite " Bion " will only carry species of the same sex.
There was an experiment with rats sent with their fetus into space.
In principle, nothing supernatural has been discovered.
