Poland and the Cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, it is the second member state of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always meet understanding.
I would like to mention, for example, A. <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld's lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the listeners cold and years later <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, <0xC5><0xA0>ternfeld was awarded the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch Prize in France for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned astronaut propagandist, his contribution being rewarded in part by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the moon's hidden face.
In 1925, a drain was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also unclear whether the rocket was intended to propel or brake the drain.
The only known information about this drain is that of the press of the time.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to rockets.
The research was conducted by the Kom<0xC3><0xB3>rka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
It is apparent from the documents retained that this research had reached the testing stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the search stopped.
In 1937, plans for a photoelectric rocket, designed by the engineer Rohozinski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
These two projects were aimed at military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
This committee had been created in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works on aeronautics were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is talk of a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Probleme, which contains four more detailed articles devoted to aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society devoted to astronautics.
By that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the International Astronautical Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz Zaraniewicz (1902–1959), became vice-president of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) weather rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to conduct scientific research.
The first model, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version, the RM-1A, was built and, during the summer of 1959, two-stage rocket flight tests of the RM-2 were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket was 1.4 meters long and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, succeeded the first rockets of the RM type.
This rocket, designed with two stages, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of craft was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Later, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
The entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
As part of the Interkosmos program, Poland also participated in space exploration on artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this program.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court overturned the Public Works Act.
This decision has given rise to a lively discussion in the public mind.
It is certainly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalisation, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This means in concrete terms that the different economic entities as well as the national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of the freedom of trade and the free movement (without limits) of private capital allied to unbridled financial speculation.
The considerable differences in the price of labour (wage) generate a tension on prices.
This term should be understood as meaning that a producer strives to resist economic competition by "making more expensive" the price of the competitor, in order to remove a larger share of the market and thereby increase its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either transferring production abroad, or buying at low prices, or disappearing. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus no responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the state necessarily increase.
All this situation intensifies the perfect ill will of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate the economic and social damage caused to the whole society by this race for the benefit of.
This situation is at such a point of public notoriety that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
The unscrupulous practices of private capital create in the different economies a situation in which the governments of the different countries are forced to engage in a mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments put their own population at the mercy of private capital without taking into account social collapse.
This is mainly reflected in the amendments to the laws in force.
The aim is to force economically its own population to accept the dictates of the prices of private capital, especially in the field of wages.
This is done on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other by the restriction of the rights of employees in the field of labour legislation.
The result is growing poverty and deepening differences between the rich and the poor.
In RFA, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years that cannot provide for their needs with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
In the context of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is becoming quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is forced to pay a supplement in order for them to reach the vital minimum.
For example, such a scandal has been updated in the case of employees working as auxiliaries in the federal parliament.
The economic measures of practically all the Member States of the south of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as was the case in the nineteenth century), or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of capital, in the private sector.
The question must be asked here: where will this capital come from?
If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turkish, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European salary.
This also applies to the whole of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim, weary of it, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the directed economy leads to an economic catastrophe.
Private capital strongly defends the idea that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
One must then ask oneself whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not today, according to its own selfish interests, direct politics and, by the same token, the whole state.
The answer to this question is undoubtedly yes.
The proof of this is that there is a virtually omnipotent lobby present in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifesting itself in the field of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemnable but not punishable.
In RFA, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, national departments delegate the drafting of laws to law firms closely related to the industry.
These bills are then passed in the Bundestag.
The totality of power does not come from the people, as the Western-style constitutions declare, but from powerful financial groups serving their own interests.
It is clear that liberal-oriented democracies are now quickly confronted with the situation described by Appianos in his book entitled "The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Time of Caesar and Pompey": "The state was long in decline and the functions were attributed to violence.
Whistle blows, illegally obtained favors, and stones and swords were also used to obtain these positions.
The under-tables and corruption proliferated without limits and the people went to the elections with votes already sold. ... ... " The honest people did not at all seek to obtain functions, it resulted once the state remained 8 months without consuls." ... "It really began to be said that the remedy to this difficult situation was an autocracy and that it was an autocracy.
In conclusion, as in antiquity, the present society is based on the preference of personal profit, without regard for the interest of society as a whole.
In essence, private capital is no longer capable of understanding and asserting the interests of society as a whole.
The result is, today as in the past, an unprecedented decadence of the elites, without any effort to carry out reforms in depth.
We must therefore look for the causes of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the unscrupulous liberalization of the economic systems of the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.
In the current state of affairs, the disappearance of these systems for the benefit of liberal democracies can be considered as a kind of pause before a new stage.
The fact that the current elites are completely unaware of the possibility of hundreds of thousands of future loss of life, the humanitarian and social crises of which we are witness today, as well as the crimes against humanity as we know them from ancient and recent history.
Repeal of the Public Works Act is not a solution, at least in the long term.
Under the pressure of economic competition, both at the international level and at the European internal level, the Government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to reduce the social level of the population.
This trend is indeed systemic.
The solution consists of socio-political reforms, which will strengthen the state's capital investments in the economy, increase the influence of citizens on the government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society for the benefit of the state.
