The architects of the firm MVRDV prove that true adventures are not just a matter of imagination. To be convinced of this, it is enough to contemplate Spijkenisse and the newly erected mountain of books - 2 photos
"I think this building is fun, it's very futuristic, finally something interesting to see," says Lisette Verhaig, a passerby on the lower side of the street.
Stefan Spermon, a computer scientist at a large neighboring company, tells us, “Yes, it’s really beautiful, this building.”
But I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has the Internet, an iPad, and e-books.
Today, no one goes willingly in one of these shabby libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The 80,000-soul municipality has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to give back some neurons to the brain, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of pretty small miniatures in painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
Thus the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get their hands on the statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam office of architects MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of witty and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with his usual phlegm and entered the competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at each other, bewildered and raising their shoulders, Maas, the confrontational, stacked his choice books in order of size to make it a pyramid, and finished his speech supported by activist arguments by a: "common dog!"
Here it is, my proposal for the mountain of books of Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>30 million mountain has sprung up.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and townhouses for a total of 50 homes.
In early November, the mountain of books received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
This is how this small, dull village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a town hall of stunning ugliness, whose white facades invite you to think that they are home to a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The Long Road to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Sure, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the true joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you walk through the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The interior made entirely of glass is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant spotlights speak unequivocally the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking for public benches, dogs and little boys and little girls playing ball.
And everywhere books, books and more books.
“Normally, the library beams are located along the facade and in the middle is a large, dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,” explains Willy Maas.
We have completely upset the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside out.
The interior of the mountain of books has been neatly arranged: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environment center and the technical center of the building.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes slabs, sometimes railings, sometimes stair ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the hardened architects and engineers of the building do not want unknown materials.
“We wanted to work with recycled materials,” says Joop Trouborst, head of the project at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found in a Frisian agricultural company an ad hoc waste from agriculture.
In the Netherlands, synthetic membranes of one millimeter thick have been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we save time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be thrown away.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 meters, the literary cafe offers us a breathtaking view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they mainly contribute to maintaining the ideal level of humidity in the air of the literary mountain.
Donations for the New Soul
“It’s incredible, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in terms of ecology,” says Trouborst.
The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is located under a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior for a short time, even on good weather days.
The thick wooden beams mounted across the glass facade serve as a sunshade, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the aforementioned septic computer scientist, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even described the Boekenberg as Spijkenisse's "soul finally found".
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure allowed to fill the voids of the library that was not yet completely filled (today it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all sides.
For architect Winy Maas, "there is nothing worse than a half-empty library."
“I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's just for decoration."
Thus MVRDV has achieved the master discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page in literary history.
Even though she may seem young and uneducated.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "The Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose to abstain in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian state.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinians' request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstinence.
Why? !
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must exercise caution, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think that it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose to abstain in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
Finally, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany experiencing difficulties in adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is revising its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so to speak defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans are fighting on several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find that role, but they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
Foreign policy, such as in France or Great Britain
What, then, does the term “normal” foreign policy mean to the Germans?
It shows a willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national files.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, therefore by its exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are, to a certain extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
