Prosecutors tried to demonstrate Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of being behind the largest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. military -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claims he suffered during his military detention.
During a cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney Maj. Ashden Fein stated that records of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine-month detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints regarding his treatment.
The cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defense filed a motion demanding that the Manning case be classified on the grounds that the kidnapping took place under very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- took place one day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
This military intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein and Manning examined the forms officers had filled out after their meeting with Manning, during his detention in Quantico Military Prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers asked questions to Manning and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that the treatment he received from his guards was "excellent" and that the treatment he had received in prison was overall "very professional."
The forms do not report any complaints of ill-treatment, although officers directly questioned her about her incarceration, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had orally expressed concerns about certain issues and that visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the issues raised.
