Military Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment during an interview in January 2011 with the special commission that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a “risk of injury.”
The military said they had assigned him that restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for risk of suicide -- for his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was doing well, and I wanted to be stripped of that status... in order to benefit from a better quality of life from my point of view,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps base military prison in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
