But more and more, some academics and experts specializing in child development praise boredom.
It’s perfectly normal for us – and our children – to get bored from time to time, they say.
This forces the brain to take interesting paths, or even to nurture creativity.
And since we are, for the most part, constantly in front of several types of screens, we no longer know the benefits of boredom.
So should we welcome boredom with open arms?
Oh, yeah.
And no.
But I'll come back.
First of all, like many people, I thought boredom was a fairly recent phenomenon, especially since we have more free time.
But this is not the case, says Peter Toohey, professor of Greco-Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of "Boredom: A Lively History" (Yale University Press, 2011).
“The boredom goes back a long way,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are Latin graffiti that evoke boredom, they go back to the first century.
Then there is the definition that we give to boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined, and debated, in different ways, said John D. Eastwood, associate professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After going through many publications and submitting the idea to a discussion group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as an experience that consists of "wanting to do something, but failing to get into a satisfying activity."
What differentiates boredom from apathy, he says, is that the person is not undertaking a task although they would like to.
With apathy, he says, there is no desire to do anything.
What is at the heart of boredom, he said, is “the interruption of the attention process, associated with a moody mood and the feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boring can be very similar to depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that if the two can be linked, bored people tend to think the problem comes from the environment or the world, while depressed people think the problem comes from them.
Sometimes we think that we are bored when it is actually a problem of concentration.
As part of their study, "The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention," which was published in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science in September, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues highlighted an older experiment in which participants listened to a tape, the voice of a person in the train.
Some groups heard, coming from the next room, the too loud sound of a TV show that had no report, others just heard the TV show, and the third group did not hear the tape at all.
Those who heard the TV at a low sound level said they were more bored than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, but didn't know why, and attributed this problem of concentration to boredom.
When you try to focus on a difficult or busy task, a distraction can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when you’re doing a boring task, “like looking at objects on a editing string, music can help you not get bored.”
In fact, he says, we now know that when you twist or scratch, these gestures, often seen as signs of boredom, are actually a good way to stay physically more alert.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to giggle learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to remain motionless,” said Professor Fenske.
We all get bored one day or another - the delay of my flight, a speaker with a monochord voice, a particularly boring film.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To measure this, researchers developed a “boring predisposition scale” in the 1980s.
The scale includes statements such as, “Among the tasks I perform, many of them are repetitive and monotonous,” and “I have so many interests that I don’t have time to do everything.”
Using such a scale, the researchers found that boys tend to get bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a psychology professor at the University of West Florida, and in particular need of numerous and varied stimulations.
But in general, teenagers are quickly blasé.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of individual and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day via a beeper.
It found that 32 percent of teens reported being bored at school and during homework, while 23 percent reported being bored when they were not at school.
In contrast, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentages of boredom today, or 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he added that he knew that “adolescents are a time when boredom reaches its highest level,” particularly because children and teens don’t have much control over what they want to do.
If I ask my question, is boredom good for you?
Sometimes not, because in its extreme form, it can cause people to take absurd physical risks, make bets or abuse certain substances to pass the time, as studies show.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers mention a link between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying the problem for more than two decades.
“Boost is the way the brain has found to let you know that you should do something else,” said Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at N.Y.U.
But the brain doesn’t always know which is the most appropriate thing to do.
If you get bored and use that energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
But if you watch TV, it will make you happy in the short term, but not in the long term.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will not be bored anymore, but he will not have learned to take care of himself or to self-regulate, says Professor Fenske.
And “this self-regulation goes from one situation to another,” he says.
Your child not only learns to have fun, he gets more mastery of himself in other areas.
I don't think we should glorify boredom.
Just as I don't think we should criticize him either.
Feeling comfortable outside of the constant whirlpool that generate activities and technology is the goal we should aim for.
Professor Eastwood agrees on this point.
“We need to get bored more often, but boredom awakens an acute and frantic desire to be connected to something that makes sense,” he said.
According to him, what people are looking for is a way to disconnect and appreciate downtime.
“In an environment where we’re constantly hyperstimulated,” he added, “it’s hard to find ways to get into something when the noise stops.”
