The hardest job in the world: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian volcano bearers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by carrying sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulfuric gas emanating from the earth's interior solidifies in contact with the air.
After collecting large sulfur rocks, which weigh a total of almost 70 kilograms, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There is only 250 meters up to the summit of the volcano which peaks at 2,386 meters altitude, but the worn-out carriers take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle-like appearance, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents euros for every kilogram of sulfur extracted.
Once up, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets painfully, they walk the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company has installed a little below at 1,850 meters of altitude.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, one might say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) per kilo of sulfur.
It then sells it at 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even serves to whiten sugar.
“As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” says Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and ends up exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although this seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is triple what he would gain in the fields.
“The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros) per day and where the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” says the bearer who once worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.20 euros) per day and the job was not so difficult, but Anto returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as sulfur: "I married a young girl from Bali, for whom they are hin
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At the age of 27, he spent three of his life defying danger on the Kawah ljen, but sulfur has already begun to make him pay the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases emitted by the volcano.
This is the price he has to pay to pursue his dream.
“I’m going to work for another two years, because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Malminated by life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or receptionist in a hotel, but instead he does the work of a mule.
It shares an unhealthy mass of wood with other carriers, rising every day at two o'clock in the morning because sulfur does not stop gushing at night, when its characteristic yellow color becomes blue and shines in the midst of darkness.
Defying the darkness, Anto descends into the crater by lighting himself with a small lamp attached to his helmet, which he bought himself with his own money.
Some 400 carriers load the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its comfortable benefits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to bearers who work on their account and are paid by weight.
In addition, they also do not touch one of the 30,000 rupees (2.50 euros) increase per camera, in addition to the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.20 euros), which the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This work is done for animals, not humans,” protested Madrusin, a 42-year-old corpulent porter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for thirty years since he left college.
Able to carry up to 110 kilos, he assures that he will not stop working "as long as he can", as he needs money to raise his 3 sons, aged between 10 and 18 years.
I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, osteoarthritis, pain due to deformities and pain in the joints.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, 53, can only load 50 kilos.
Every day, his companions and he extract 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a path of goats invaded by weeds.
"I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano is my whole life," Unainik says, opening his mouth, revealing several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulfur wearer.
Time passes, but the misery continues from generation to generation one of the most difficult jobs in the world: the one made by the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
Singapore Seeks Babies to Save the Economy
Singaporeans blame this lack of children on career, stress and the cost of access to property.
"Singapore's population needs to grow."
I am a husband and a patriot, you are my wife and a patriot, let's fulfill our civic duty and give life!
It may seem unlikely that these words come from an advertisement for mint pills, but despite this, or perhaps because of this, the video spread like a trail of powder on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references such as "Let's put a polychinelle in the drawer" to mock Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way thanks to this ad.
His creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music for people to fulfill “their national duty.”
It is intended only for the Internet, so we were able to make it fun and entertaining.
This is the main problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world in the field of birth, so we felt that it was a topic that we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things like throwing perfumes at pheromones or organizing speed-dating parties.
Many of these ideas were creative but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought to ourselves, what could be more creative about solving this problem than making it a rap song?
1.2 children
The government of Singapore does not take it lightly.
He spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage his citizens to have more children.
A government measure for marriages and fathers grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and distributes tax benefits.
But all this had little effect.
Singapore is a rich and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore, according to its national population distribution, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered as the renewal rate, was in 1976.
Why don’t Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Division, said it was due to “better education” and “a wider choice of career opportunities.”
“This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond marriage and the constitution of a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to an increase in the number of singles and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at radically increasing immigration to counter population decline has created resentment within the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites that abound with barely disguised xenophobia against new immigrants, especially against Chinese who are accused of pulling wages down and not integrating.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the ruling party in Singapore last year experienced its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem by setting higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example also has unexpected consequences.
The government is trying to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, this began to affect the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and their sale is very successful.
However, the authorities are concerned that they may promote a single lifestyle and discourage promoters wishing to build large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate company EL Developers, says his “shoeboxes” are selling out much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these housings are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it is much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously put in the wheel if they wanted to offer too many small housing in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations can be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by discussing with Singaporeans working in the financial district of the center, it would seem that they are not going to have much effect.
“People are very stressed, homes are expensive, just like education, that’s why people put it off later,” says one young executive.
Other people can have children.
“But for me, it’s important to be able to have my money and my time,” another 20-year-old tells us.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of access to property and education as the reasons for preventing them from having children.
Thus, although the government is trying to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the final say.
