The UNASUR summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public.
The 6th Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the Lima Declaration being made public, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the 7 representatives present.
Efe has tried several times to access the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be released after the summit closed, then claimed that it would be published from time to time on the government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its contents had been exposed by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information circulating among the journalists was that given by the press attachés of some of the Unasur governments attending the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, Peru’s presidency sent an email to the media with the summit’s “final declaration,” but it was President Humala’s speech and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit of the Arab South America (ASPA) and, on this occasion, although this was requested by the press, it also did not broadcast the statement also called the Lima Declaration, as it had previously been announced.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to put in place secure transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited the obtaining of information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Court of The Hague that defines a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebasti<0xC3><0xA1>n Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met at the regional meeting and said they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the arguments of both sides in the trial that Lima has tried against Santiago, which begins Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing today before this international court," President Humala said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, treaties and international courts,” said President Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, handing over a hand to President Humala, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of this international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously flawed.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Ch<0xC3><0xA1>vez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was tasked with opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total of 17 million dollars of investment.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the countries of the Unasur would put in place "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for better access to medicines, low-cost Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters."
With Europe in crisis, “the economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our populations,” concluded President Humala.
“We have decided to favour a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” he said in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the transverse axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador although he did not give further details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process of this country will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations," of which he is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, next Saturday in Mexico City to calmly discuss the maritime dispute through an ICJ judgment requested by Bogota.
"It's possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," Santos said.
"We are going to revise all these ways, they are not exhaustive, including the treaty with Nicaragua that will ask to have a discussion with this country," he said.
“I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will settle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to attend the inauguration of the country’s new president, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto.
In the same way, as part of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc will meet in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus in terms of defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
“South America needs to learn from Europe how to integrate citizenship,” Correa said.
