He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmas.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because he was speechless".
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and have a good quality of life.
However, ignoring their illness, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, “exhausted” their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the population in general is exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, and he took this scientific information as a reference.
The HIV/AIDS infectiologist and expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a deadly disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depended on the level of allocation of the immune system that patients presented at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those who did not consume a drug for years.
To put it simply, this means that for someone who is diagnosed with HIV at age 25, “as long as they remain under control, they will be able to live without problems for up to 75 years,” the scientist explained.
In order to place this progress in its context, it is necessary to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans today is an average of 76 years.
While it is true that mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of AIDS-related deaths has increased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), but it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60 per cent of the nationally identified patients are on the basis of data.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths as of May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I don't think the problem comes from access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
In the last 12 years at least, we have never lacked drugs, the problem is that patients arrive at very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or else they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
“Nine out of ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to make earlier diagnoses and, for that, we need to offer massive screening tests to all people who ask for it.”
Specialists and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention of Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to do his screening test in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done it and that, despite his young age, he was already a carrier of AIDS and suffocating cane.
