Thus, it would appear that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican laws are not valid in the country with the star banner, in contrast to international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the judgment rendered last June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the Northern District of Texas, leaves Mexican companies defenseless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond the Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow Mexico’s top glassmaker to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge of the case points out that creditors must register under the U.S. Bankruptcy Act, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, sitting in New Orleans, asserts that the main procedure is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would involve denouncing international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
In fact, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of International Commercial Law had been created for this purpose by taking the American Law Institute as an arbitrator.
