Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The globe-trotting basketball player "Hetin" Reyes has spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as great as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a brain hemorrhage condemned him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a player of lower leagues, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Vaqueros de Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n as president-feker of both the Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n and the president-feker of the Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n.
“I’ve worn several basketball caps throughout my life, and even several at the same time, like when I was president of BSN, director general of the national team and president of the federation during the 90s,” Reyes recalls during a visit to Primera Hora’s home in Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n, where he has been living with Isabel, his fiancee of 50 years.
“Basketball has been my whole life.
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this claim.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories that remind him of his extraordinary itinerary, bear witness to this.
Bayam<0xC3><0xB3>n in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves the most are those that remind him of his time as a player in the team of the Vaqueros in the mid-50s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
“It’s been my best years, those I’ve taken the most advantage of because I’ve had the chance to participate in eight Cowboys championships since 1967, whether as a manager, co-manager or manager.
This has been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships played from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired from the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been in charge here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), telling me, "I have a tough player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
This is how to start Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has had.
Bartow then recommended me to Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He enjoyed the championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse, but only remotely since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At the time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's responsibilities in the national team.
I remember when we won it for the first time in the United States at the pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we came 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge had not made us play the last game again, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She is one of the best, as well as the one who beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympic Games.
But my favorite is the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba, when we won the gold and we raked the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the team that won the bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only made up of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico L<0xC3><0xB3>pez and "Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n" (Ortiz), there were also the young (Javier) "To<0xC3><0xB1>ito" Col<0xC3><0xB3>n and James Carter, the brothers Le<0xC3><0xB3>n (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the World Cup.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy during the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and the young Rolando Hourrutiner replacing players suspended by the imbroglio of the Pan American Games of Mar del Plata, we won the gold against all odds.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Without a doubt, this is Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n Ortiz.
His statistics at the international tournaments are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico has dominated at this level like Picul<0xC3><0xAD>n did.
And this without taking into account his trajectory in the different leagues for which he played.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team composed of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
As a young man, I love the work that Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest achievement within the federation?
Having been part of the most glorious era of the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s, the BSN had up to 17 teams in one season.
What's left for you to do?
There are things that I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalization of the minor categories.
For example, the Ponce boys only play in their area and only face teams from other corners of the island during the national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when it is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for leaders, field staff and referees.
That makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, watch clips from my time on YouTube, enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, attend basketball games.
And of course, I enjoy the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931, in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide by the leading role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he played an unscrupulous, fearful and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., the production house of "Dallas."
“Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, playing the ironic role he loved most,” the family said.
Larry’s family and close friends were with him in Dallas on this Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, said his press officer, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented, and I will miss him very much.
“He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the full,” Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed liver cirrhosis to Larry Hagman in 1992 and he had admitted to drinking heavily for many years.
In 1995, he had been diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had undergone a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had made himself known on television in the role of an ordinary guy in the series "Jinny of my dreams" broadcast by NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an alluring genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film roles include well-received critical roles in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully detestable J.R. that Larry Hagman enjoyed his greatest success.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and their loved ones aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who Killed J.R.?", invented to entertain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which Hagman's character is almost murdered, has generated speculation worldwide and millions of dollars played in wagers.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached a record audience at that time.
When the answer was revealed in a November 1980 episode, 41 million viewers were on average in front of their screen and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had pregnant her and then threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable but charismatic smiling man: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who was trying to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) interned.
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," Hagman said in 1988.
We should write, "Here's the honest citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only part he's lost.
Victoria Principal, co-star of the original series, recalled this Friday Hagman as a "huge man, both on the small screen and in life".
It is unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the heart of each and every one of us, who have had the chance to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already completed for the second season and a sixth is in progress, the channel has informed.
For now, neither Warner nor TNT have communicated how Hagman's death will be integrated into the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he is the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who rose to fame with classic works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
Mary Martin was still a teenager when she gave birth to her in 1931 while she was married to lawyer Ben Hagman.
He made his first steps on the New York theater scene in the early 1950s and served in the Air Force from 1952 to 1956 in England.
It was there that he met the young Swedish interior designer Maj Axelsson and married him.
The couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and lived for many years in the California town of Malibu, where many celebrities reside.
In 2001, he titled his memoirs "Hello Darlin': Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life" (in French: Hello Darlin': Les mémoires impitoyables de J.R)
“I didn’t write anything in this book that could hurt someone or affect them in any way,” he told reporters at the time.
After his liver transplant, he became an active organ donation activist and worked as a volunteer in a hospital to assist concerned patients.
"I advise them, I restore their confidence, I come with them when they come to have surgery and after," he says in 1996.
I try to offer them a little comfort, like, "Don't be afraid, it won't be easy for a little while, but it's going to be okay."
