A course dealing with the "End of the World" has just begun
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to give a class on the end of the world, he knew he was throwing an irresistible hook there: the end of the Mayan calendar’s “big countdown” on December 21, which many people refer to as proof of the end of the impending world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the months that followed: catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal chasm that some have dubbed "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where late-time Christian theorists thought it would trigger.
“I didn’t realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I’ve ever known,” Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey.
If we analyze what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And we must remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he’s not the only teacher to give classes on “the end of the world” this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches Media, Culture and the End of the World.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
“We analyze this because these ideas proliferate over time,” he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides certain human behavior.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared to real-life examples.
“I tried to inform my students about what was possible, probable, credible, and impossible,” Vacker said.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a course, simply titled "The End of the World."
“We’re adding ‘2012’ to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world doesn’t disappear,” said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and pass their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be passed on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work “until the very night of the supposed end of the world,” Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
“It was complete in two hours,” Restall said of his course for high-level students, consisting of 35 students.
We received emails several weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there was still room.
Students, for their part, ensure that the course is one of the most interesting.
“It fascinates me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves,” says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student in religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers-Camden University.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic movies.
“I had never heard of a course that taught this subject,” he said.
I appreciate it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a professor, told us to believe in the end-of-the-world date of December 21.
“Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,” says Julie Zegle, a 21-year-old graduate student at Temple and a native of West Chester.
The Mayans never predicted the end of the world, it’s just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is an apocalypse-related anxiety in Western culture, going back several centuries, that causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has sparked a surge of speculation.
“In other parts of the world, people don’t think about it,” he says.
This is mostly in the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew we were teaching here on “the end of the world.”
“The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,” he replied, as if it were an exception coming from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall notes that over the years, there has been talk of the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he claims that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing about the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Many told us that they thought they were going to "end of the world" parties.
“Sometimes I call friends and we laugh about it together,” said Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
